00:29:53.476 --> 00:29:57.276
It's not multiple cycles of chemotherapy, how we give systemically.

500
00:29:57.776 --> 00:30:01.676
And there are different agents that are given intraperitoneally for this HIPEC,

501
00:30:01.716 --> 00:30:05.520
and herein lies some of the controversies.There

502
00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:09.040
are other intraperitoneal strategies that are being developed to try and

503
00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:12.020
deliver various systemic therapies into the abdomen.

504
00:30:12.500 --> 00:30:16.220
For colorectal cancer, particularly apart from HIPEC is PIPAC,

505
00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:20.230
which is a pressurized intraperitoneal chemotherapy delivered

506
00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:23.460
through a laparoscope with essentially an

507
00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:26.880
aerosolizer that allows you to deliver high-pressured

508
00:30:26.900 --> 00:30:28.960
chemotherapeutic agents into the abdomen.

509
00:30:29.300 --> 00:30:33.100
But as of today, most of the time, the drugs that are

510
00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:35.980
being delivered into the peritoneum are still chemotherapeutic

511
00:30:36.020 --> 00:30:37.420
agents.

512
00:30:39.240 --> 00:30:42.700
And this was a study that was now published more than 20 years ago.

513
00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:47.060
This is a Dutch group that did a randomized trial

514
00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:50.960
in the era of colorectal cancer systemic therapies that were

515
00:30:51.040 --> 00:30:53.750
very, very weak. Most patients only got

516
00:30:53.860 --> 00:30:57.680
5-fluorouracil and leucovorin as their treatment for metastatic disease.

517
00:30:58.140 --> 00:30:58.930
And in this study,

518
00:31:00.020 --> 00:31:03.880
in about 100 patients, they were randomized to either receive systemic

519
00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:07.700
therapy or to receive what was defined as aggressive

520
00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:10.140
cytoreductive surgery as well as HIPEC.

521
00:31:10.500 --> 00:31:11.680
And in this 50-patient

522
00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:17.020
per arm study, there was a survival benefit for the patients that

523
00:31:17.060 --> 00:31:19.260
received the HIPEC compared to the ones that didn't.

524
00:31:19.700 --> 00:31:23.060
And this set this entire path down this

525
00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.700
space, talking about the fact that

526
00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:30.540
maybe patients with peritoneal metastases should get CRS and HIPEC

527
00:31:30.820 --> 00:31:32.500
compared to just getting chemotherapy alone.

528
00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:36.750
But keep in mind that the comparator arm was very non-standard

529
00:31:36.750 --> 00:31:40.000
chemotherapy that's currently contemporary.

530
00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:43.140
So for about 20 years,

531
00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:47.500
we didn't have any other randomized data to support

532
00:31:48.280 --> 00:31:52.120
CRS and HIPEC until about five years ago now, the PRODIGE

533
00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:55.540
07 study was published. This was a much larger

534
00:31:55.880 --> 00:31:59.440
randomized trial across France with multiple different

535
00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:04.400
groups participating in it. And this had more than

536
00:32:04.840 --> 00:32:08.700
250 patients, where the question that was asked very specifically

537
00:32:08.710 --> 00:32:12.420
was not whether cytoreductive surgery was meaningful, but whether

538
00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.000
HIPEC was meaningful. So in this study, all patients actually got

539
00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:19.540
cytoreductive surgery but were randomized to then receive HIPEC.

540
00:32:19.560 --> 00:32:23.400
And as you can see here, that the HIPEC actually had no survival benefit,

541
00:32:23.720 --> 00:32:26.860
with both the arms actually having very similar survival.

542
00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:29.440
And this set the entire field into chaos because

543
00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:34.260
now came questions of whether delivering intraperitoneal chemotherapy, at least in

544
00:32:34.280 --> 00:32:36.660
a one-time setting with HIPEC, was meaningful.

545
00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:40.990
Keep in mind that the HIPEC was actually using a drug called oxaliplatin, and

546
00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:44.980
there are some criticisms around this, and this has now been trying

547
00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.240
to be studied in different ways. After this, there were

548
00:32:48.560 --> 00:32:51.830
multiple other trials that were also reporting with negative

549
00:32:51.900 --> 00:32:55.500
data. The COLO-PEC trial actually looked at doing adjuvant HIPEC

550
00:32:55.600 --> 00:32:59.370
after surgery, trying to prevent colorectal peritoneal

551
00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:03.320
metastases, and again, we can see there was no survival benefit for doing

552
00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:06.520
HIPEC after primary tumor resections.

553
00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:10.520
Similarly, the French group had another study called PROFYLO-CHIP,

554
00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:12.960
where they were trying to do

555
00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:14.840
prevention of

556
00:33:16.080 --> 00:33:19.930
recurrence of peritoneal metastases after the original resection,

557
00:33:19.980 --> 00:33:23.780
and even in this study, there was no survival benefit for doing the second-look

558
00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:24.320
HIPEC.

559
00:33:26.120 --> 00:33:29.420
More recently, we saw data from the HIPEC-T4 study from the Spanish group,

560
00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:33.270
where patients who were at high risk of having peritoneal metastases,

561
00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:35.700
typically T4 primary tumors,

562
00:33:36.900 --> 00:33:38.740
were then randomized to receive HIPEC.

563
00:33:39.060 --> 00:33:42.820
And the trial had an unusual primary endpoint

564
00:33:42.860 --> 00:33:46.570
of local regional control rate, where the HIPEC showed

565
00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:51.340
an improvement of local control, and this

566
00:33:51.360 --> 00:33:53.640
was actually published a couple of years ago now.

567
00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:57.680
But very recently, just a couple of months ago, they published the

568
00:33:57.740 --> 00:34:01.400
overall survival data, and actually, there was completely no benefit for

569
00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:05.160
overall survival, which means that while some peritoneal disease was being

570
00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:09.040
controlled, the patients were not living longer with the delivery of the

571
00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:09.480
HIPEC.

572
00:34:10.821 --> 00:34:14.761
And also, just last year, we saw the data from the CAIRO6 trial, where,

573
00:34:15.680 --> 00:34:15.940
again,

574
00:34:17.020 --> 00:34:20.580
a relatively unusual way of designing the study where both

575
00:34:21.759 --> 00:34:25.580
arms actually got HIPEC, but then one arm also got systemic therapy,

576
00:34:25.660 --> 00:34:29.500
which is typically not the way we treat our patients with metastatic disease.

577
00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:33.190
And this study actually showed there's no benefit of the systemic chemotherapy,

578
00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:37.220
although this has multiple criticisms to it and has not been

579
00:34:37.240 --> 00:34:37.670
considered

580
00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:39.980
practice-changing at this point in time.

581
00:34:40.060 --> 00:34:44.040
So as of today, the current treatment algorithms and paradigms--

582
00:34:44.120 --> 00:34:45.680
Whoops, that's not good.

583
00:34:53.680 --> 00:34:55.480
So as you can see, after the first

584
00:34:56.460 --> 00:35:00.160
Dutch study in 2003, which was positive, there have been multiple negative trials

585
00:35:00.200 --> 00:35:04.020
for HIPEC. And as of today, the guidelines actually

586
00:35:04.140 --> 00:35:07.620
seem to suggest that there may be a role for cytoreductive surgery and systemic

587
00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:11.620
therapy for patients with peritoneal metastases, but the role of HIPEC is

588
00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:15.200
still being questioned, and at least oxaliplatin-based HIPEC has been

589
00:35:15.260 --> 00:35:18.620
recommended as not to be added after cytoreductive surgery.

590
00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:22.520
And so the patients who do undergo cytoreductive surgery

591
00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:26.250
often now get mitomycin-based chemotherapy if

592
00:35:26.280 --> 00:35:29.920
HIPEC is being delivered, but the guidelines are quite weak for these

593
00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:33.880
recommendations. And it is because of this, there's a lot of nihilism that's

594
00:35:34.760 --> 00:35:38.160
set into place in this peritoneal metastases realm.

595
00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:39.080
And

596
00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:44.160
those of us in the translation space are hoping to shift this by trying to

597
00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:47.480
understand the biology of colorectal peritoneal metastases.

598
00:35:47.860 --> 00:35:51.350
And so over the next few slides, we'll talk a little bit about what we are trying

599
00:35:51.380 --> 00:35:53.480
to do to differentiate out are

600
00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:56.580
all colorectal peritoneal metastases the same?

601
00:35:56.620 --> 00:35:58.510
Should we be doing something different for some of these

602
00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:02.496
patients?And so Dr. Ra spoke

603
00:36:02.556 --> 00:36:06.436
about the TCGA, which is the usual molecular classifier for

604
00:36:06.496 --> 00:36:10.366
most tumor types. But in colorectal cancer, we actually use the consensus molecular

605
00:36:10.436 --> 00:36:14.356
classification that divides out colorectal cancers

606
00:36:14.376 --> 00:36:18.296
into four different subgroups. The subgroup of interest to us is going to

607
00:36:18.316 --> 00:36:21.896
be CMS four, which usually has a high rate of copy number

608
00:36:21.936 --> 00:36:25.656
aberrations, stromal infiltration, TGF-beta activation,

609
00:36:25.776 --> 00:36:28.636
angiogenesis, and typically has a poorer prognosis.

610
00:36:29.286 --> 00:36:33.216
And the reason we use the consensus molecular classification is because compared

611
00:36:33.256 --> 00:36:36.956
to the TCGA in colorectal cancer, they actually had multiple groups with

612
00:36:37.036 --> 00:36:38.756
fairly large numbers of samples that

613
00:36:39.636 --> 00:36:42.656
did primary tumor classifications to come up with this.

614
00:36:43.056 --> 00:36:44.396
And the CMS four

615
00:36:45.676 --> 00:36:47.656
subgroup, as we said, has actually a higher

616
00:36:48.996 --> 00:36:52.916
presence of mesenchymal subtype and cancer stem cells with higher

617
00:36:52.976 --> 00:36:56.536
rates of EMT activation, TGF-beta activation, and matrix

618
00:36:56.576 --> 00:37:00.436
remodeling, as well as angiogenesis that are upregulated in

619
00:37:00.456 --> 00:37:02.716
this subgroup.

620
00:37:04.676 --> 00:37:08.636
We do know that the colorectal peritoneal metastasis patients do have

621
00:37:08.676 --> 00:37:11.356
an enrichment for the CMS four subgroup.

622
00:37:12.456 --> 00:37:13.976
This was an early study that

623
00:37:15.156 --> 00:37:18.976
differentiated out primary tumors and peritoneal tumors, and we can see

624
00:37:19.036 --> 00:37:22.556
that there is a higher number of CMS four subgroup peritoneal tumors.

625
00:37:23.036 --> 00:37:26.976
But one of the bigger papers that has been done is this study that was

626
00:37:27.016 --> 00:37:30.766
published by a Dutch group about three or four years ago now,

627
00:37:31.256 --> 00:37:35.156
where they did multi-omic profiling for about 50

628
00:37:35.276 --> 00:37:39.136
colorectal peritoneal metastases with a few primary tumors

629
00:37:39.176 --> 00:37:43.126
that were paired. And you can see, again, they showed the same thing where

630
00:37:43.126 --> 00:37:46.476
the peritoneal tumors actually had a higher rate of CMS four compared to the

631
00:37:46.496 --> 00:37:50.396
primary tumors. And the ones that were of CMS four actually had a

632
00:37:50.436 --> 00:37:53.256
poorer prognosis compared to the CMS one,

633
00:37:54.196 --> 00:37:55.516
two, or three subtypes.

634
00:37:58.876 --> 00:38:02.536
What they did go on to do then is to look at within the CMS four to come up with

635
00:38:02.656 --> 00:38:04.716
multiple subgroups within CMS four.

636
00:38:05.116 --> 00:38:08.915
And in this study, at least three different CMS

637
00:38:08.956 --> 00:38:12.816
four subgroups were identified with differential

638
00:38:13.136 --> 00:38:14.216
expressions of

639
00:38:15.956 --> 00:38:19.776
RAS mutations as well as TP53. They actually had

640
00:38:19.816 --> 00:38:22.316
differential behavior. They were labeled as

641
00:38:24.236 --> 00:38:26.376
RAS mutated mucinous or

642
00:38:28.416 --> 00:38:31.576
inflamed subgroups over here. And you can see that the tumor

643
00:38:31.636 --> 00:38:35.236
microenvironment compositions for these three different subgroups were

644
00:38:35.336 --> 00:38:36.156
actually different

645
00:38:37.256 --> 00:38:38.796
within the CMS four itself.

646
00:38:43.016 --> 00:38:46.776
And other groups have actually compared colorectal liver metastases

647
00:38:46.836 --> 00:38:50.816
compared to peritoneal metastases and again, you can see

648
00:38:50.856 --> 00:38:54.606
that the liver metastases actually don't have the CMS four as

649
00:38:54.816 --> 00:38:57.116
high compared to the peritoneal metastases.

650
00:38:57.416 --> 00:39:01.316
Again, reiterating this point of organotropism, and it is very likely

651
00:39:01.396 --> 00:39:04.856
that the gene expression programs that are being adopted by primary tumors

652
00:39:05.216 --> 00:39:08.696
will guide the organotropism to the metastatic sites.

653
00:39:08.796 --> 00:39:12.056
And the ones that have the CMS four subtype actually have an

654
00:39:12.096 --> 00:39:14.396
organotropism to the peritoneum.

655
00:39:14.436 --> 00:39:18.356
The tumors that, again, reflected these actually had a poorer prognosis

656
00:39:18.396 --> 00:39:19.716
with the CMS four subtype.

657
00:39:22.736 --> 00:39:26.716
We'll talk a little bit about a paper that we published last year where this

658
00:39:26.756 --> 00:39:30.056
was probably one of the largest multi-omic profiling of colorectal

659
00:39:30.116 --> 00:39:33.936
peritoneal metastases to date in about 120 patients and about

660
00:39:33.976 --> 00:39:37.956
200 over samples with about 30 to 40 paired primary

661
00:39:38.016 --> 00:39:39.716
tumors and peritoneal metastases.

662
00:39:40.496 --> 00:39:43.436
We laid out the landscape for these tumors.

663
00:39:44.076 --> 00:39:47.876
What you can see quite consistently is actually the

664
00:39:47.916 --> 00:39:51.636
genomic landscapes between primary tumors and peritoneal metastases are

665
00:39:51.716 --> 00:39:55.436
actually very similar. There is very little differential genomic

666
00:39:55.476 --> 00:39:59.316
expressions that you can see between primary tumors, kind of reflecting

667
00:39:59.356 --> 00:40:02.836
what we know from the TCGA and CMS classification.

668
00:40:02.876 --> 00:40:06.676
The most common mutations that we were seeing in peritoneal metastases were

669
00:40:06.996 --> 00:40:09.516
TP53, APC, as well as KRAS.

670
00:40:12.276 --> 00:40:16.016
And this is not just our group. Even the Dutch group study showed the same thing.

671
00:40:16.316 --> 00:40:20.096
If you look at transcriptional expression between primary tumors and

672
00:40:20.156 --> 00:40:23.796
peritoneal metastases, you can see clear clustering between the primary

673
00:40:23.876 --> 00:40:27.556
tumors. For example, you can see that the primary tumor and peritoneal metastases

674
00:40:27.576 --> 00:40:29.816
of 39 were quite closely clustered here.

675
00:40:29.936 --> 00:40:31.696
Forty-seven was quite closely clustered here.

676
00:40:32.076 --> 00:40:35.456
But this is actually different if you look at liver metastases, where the liver

677
00:40:35.516 --> 00:40:39.466
metastases actually clustered out very separately compared to the primary

678
00:40:39.576 --> 00:40:43.556
tumors. In terms of retention of or class switching between primary

679
00:40:43.636 --> 00:40:47.516
tumors and peritoneal metastases, it was a very retained, conserved CMS four

680
00:40:47.596 --> 00:40:50.156
that was present in the peritoneal metastases.

681
00:40:50.216 --> 00:40:53.956
But you can see a lot of class switching that's occurring in the liver metastases

682
00:40:53.996 --> 00:40:56.156
space, kind of reflecting this idea that

683
00:40:57.136 --> 00:41:00.776
the seeding that's occurring for peritoneal metastases is more

684
00:41:00.876 --> 00:41:04.456
likely to be polyclonal compared to the seeding that's occurring with liver

685
00:41:04.496 --> 00:41:06.546
metastases that's more likely to be subclonal.

686
00:41:07.306 --> 00:41:09.136
And that's kind of what's alluded here.

687
00:41:09.176 --> 00:41:12.876
Again, multiple groups were showing the same thing, that the seeding for

688
00:41:12.976 --> 00:41:15.316
colorectal cancer tends to be polyclonal.

689
00:41:15.566 --> 00:41:19.186
If you look at this, you can see where they did

690
00:41:19.416 --> 00:41:23.306
single nuclei, single-cell sequencing for a very small subgroup of patients, but

691
00:41:23.316 --> 00:41:25.216
there was very conserved

692
00:41:26.356 --> 00:41:30.236
copy number aberrations that were seen when comparing primary tumors

693
00:41:30.256 --> 00:41:34.206
and peritoneal metastases. But there was quite a lot of clonal heterogeneity when

694
00:41:34.216 --> 00:41:37.976
primary tumors are compared to liver metastases, seeming to suggest what they

695
00:41:38.116 --> 00:41:38.276
were

696
00:41:39.076 --> 00:41:42.086
proposing here, that there is subtype switching and

697
00:41:42.236 --> 00:41:45.976
decreasing of the heterogeneity with a different microenvironment for

698
00:41:46.016 --> 00:41:48.936
liver metastases compared to a conserved

699
00:41:49.236 --> 00:41:53.116
microenvironment and heterogeneity compared to primary tumors

700
00:41:53.176 --> 00:41:57.116
with peritoneal metastases. This might have therapeutic implications because

701
00:41:57.136 --> 00:42:00.616
the way we think about organ-specific treatment paradigms will

702
00:42:00.696 --> 00:42:04.496
actually need to think about this idea that your peritoneal tumors are going to be

703
00:42:04.516 --> 00:42:08.376
polyclonal, and therefore you may not be able to have a specific targeted

704
00:42:08.436 --> 00:42:12.296
therapy paradigm that's going to work for peritoneal metastases

705
00:42:12.376 --> 00:42:13.836
compared to liver metastases, for

706
00:42:13.876 --> 00:42:17.684
example.In

707
00:42:17.744 --> 00:42:21.584
our study here, we also did spatial profiling looking at both

708
00:42:21.604 --> 00:42:24.344
transcriptomic as well as tumor microenvironment heterogeneity.

709
00:42:24.634 --> 00:42:28.344
And while the genomic changes that were previously

710
00:42:28.384 --> 00:42:31.564
reported were very conserved, we were now noticing differential

711
00:42:32.404 --> 00:42:35.784
transcriptomic and microenvironmental heterogeneity, especially if you go down to

712
00:42:35.804 --> 00:42:39.584
the more sophisticated spatial profiling platforms, which were

713
00:42:40.804 --> 00:42:41.074
only

714
00:42:41.884 --> 00:42:44.134
our group were the ones that showed this first.

715
00:42:44.184 --> 00:42:45.564
Where you actually see differential

716
00:42:47.124 --> 00:42:50.493
distributions of CD163 macrophages as well as

717
00:42:50.524 --> 00:42:54.454
CD68 macrophages between primary tumors

718
00:42:54.524 --> 00:42:58.464
and peritoneal metastases, seeming to suggest that from the seed and soil

719
00:42:59.224 --> 00:43:03.144
hypothesis, that once the tumors actually end up in the peritoneum, there is

720
00:43:03.224 --> 00:43:07.004
some remodeling of the peritoneal microenvironment to

721
00:43:07.084 --> 00:43:08.124
allow for this

722
00:43:09.564 --> 00:43:12.704
metastatic growth after the metastatic process has

723
00:43:13.044 --> 00:43:13.604
completed.

724
00:43:16.864 --> 00:43:20.044
And again, this is not just our group. We have other groups also.

725
00:43:20.104 --> 00:43:23.364
This is another study with a small number of liver metastases and peritoneal

726
00:43:23.384 --> 00:43:26.404
metastases, again, comparing the

727
00:43:27.304 --> 00:43:30.764
microenvironmental landscapes and showing that there is clear tumor

728
00:43:30.824 --> 00:43:34.424
microenvironmental differences between colorectal liver

729
00:43:34.464 --> 00:43:36.564
metastases and peritoneal metastases.

730
00:43:38.584 --> 00:43:41.524
In the last few minutes, I'm just going to switch to what we could do about this

731
00:43:41.544 --> 00:43:45.464
heterogeneity. This was a study that we published just a couple

732
00:43:45.524 --> 00:43:46.584
of weeks ago,

733
00:43:47.404 --> 00:43:51.004
where we took from public

734
00:43:51.084 --> 00:43:54.674
databases, multiple cell lines that were classified by CMS

735
00:43:54.704 --> 00:43:58.444
subtypes. And you can see, we looked at the different chemotherapeutic

736
00:43:58.524 --> 00:44:02.304
agents that are being used for HIPEC at this point of time, and that

737
00:44:02.944 --> 00:44:06.624
there is a difference in the way the responses are occurring to these

738
00:44:06.664 --> 00:44:10.004
different chemotherapeutic agents, that is Mitomycin C or Oxaliplatin,

739
00:44:11.884 --> 00:44:15.024
in the CMS four compared to the other CMS groups.

740
00:44:15.424 --> 00:44:19.344
Again, suggesting that maybe rather than calling the entire process

741
00:44:19.384 --> 00:44:21.524
of intraperitoneal chemotherapeutics as

742
00:44:23.164 --> 00:44:26.564
something that's not going to work, we may need to parse out what are the agents

743
00:44:26.603 --> 00:44:30.464
that we're using for these different tumor types as we're treating

744
00:44:30.504 --> 00:44:33.004
them with these intraperitoneal strategies.

745
00:44:35.164 --> 00:44:39.154
And we are also trying to develop different stromal or TME targeting

